Consider Figs. 2 and 3 illustrating logarithms of relative errors of the considered algorithm for the real and imaginary parts over the domain $0 \le x \le 10 \cap 0 \le y \le 10$, respectively. The rough surface of these plots indicates that the computation reaches the limit of double precision $\sim {10^{ - 16}}$. In particular, while $y > 0.1$ the accuracy can exceed ${10^{ - 15}}$. However, there is a narrow domain along the along $x$ axis in Fig. 2 (red color area) where the accuracy deteriorates by about an order of the magnitude. Apart from this, we can also see in Fig. 3 a sharp peak located at the origin where accuracy is $\sim {10^{ - 14}}$. Figures 4 and 5 depict these areas of the plots magnified for the real and imaginary parts, respectively. 

